Clinical results and ongoing studies with erlotinib in 
rlotinib is a low molecular weight, orally bioavailable inhibitor of  and it was the first targeted agent approved for second- and third-line treatment of  in patients unselected for  mutations. ased on the results of the .21 trial,32 erlotinib was approved by the  ood and rug dministration in 2004 for the treatment of patients with locally advanced or metastatic  after failure of at least one prior chemotherapy regimen, without restrictions in terms of molecular profile.
n 2009, osell et al obtained a median  of 28.0 months in patients receiving erlotinib as first-line therapy, as compared to 27.0 months for those treated with erlotinib after failure of prior chemotherapy.33 esults from the ptimal study, which compared erlotinib with carboplatin plus gemcitabine in hinese patients with  and  mutations, showed a median  of 13.1 months for erlotinib and 4.6 months for standard chemotherapy. rlotinib was superior also in terms of  (83% versus 36%) and tolerability.16 n the other hand, the  (uropean rlotinib ersus hemotherapy) study compared erlotinib with platinum-based chemotherapy as a first-line treatment of non-sian patients with advanced -mutant . edian  was 9.7 months in the erlotinib group and 5.2 months in the standard chemotherapy group. he main severe s were rash (13% with erlotinib and 0% with chemotherapy), neutropenia (0% versus 22%), and anemia (1% versus 4%).17 owever, erlotinib did not improve  when added to best supportive care, as compared with best supportive care alone, in chemotherapy-naive patients with poor performance status or who were unfit for platinum-based chemotherapy.34
oncerning the use of erlotinib in association with first-line chemotherapy, the drug did not confer a significant overall benefit when it was added to first-line carboplatinβ€“paclitaxel in the  (arceva. Β® Responses in Conjunction With Paclitaxel and Carboplatin) study35 or cisplatinβ€“gemcitabine in the TALENT (TarcevaΒ® Lung Cancer Investigation) study.36 Nevertheless, the analysis of a subpopulation in both studies showed significant OS benefits in never smokers treated with erlotinib.
Two additional studies, SATURN (Sequential TarcevaΒ® in Unresectable NSCLC)37 and ATLAS (A Study Comparing Bevacizumab Therapy With or Without Erlotinib for First-line Treatment of NSCLC),38 investigated the efficacy of erlotinib as maintenance therapy in locally advanced or metastatic NSCLC patients with stable disease (SD) following standard platinum-based first-line chemotherapy. Both trials reported increased PFS in patients treated with erlotinib, with the highest PFS in EGFR-mutated cases. On the other hand, the Phase III study of gemcitabine or erlotinib as maintenance therapy versus observation after cisplatinβ€“gemcitabine induction chemotherapy led by Perol et al showed a nonsignificant OS benefit.39
In the TORCH (TarcevaΒ® or Chemotherapy for the Treatment of Advanced NSCLC) study, conducted in unselected patients with advanced NSCLC, first-line erlotinib followed by second-line cisplatinβ€“gemcitabine was inferior to first-line cisplatinβ€“gemcitabine followed by second-line erlotinib. Interestingly, a relevant proportion of patients assigned to first-line chemotherapy did not receive second-line treatment.40 In the same year, the Phase III TITAN (TarcevaΒ® in Treatment of Advanced NSCLC) study, comparing erlotinib versus docetaxel or pemetrexed in chemorefractory NSCLC, showed no differences in PFS in both arms.41 Wu et al recently published the results of a Phase II trial of erlotinib as second-line treatment in patients with advanced NSCLC and asymptomatic brain metastases, showing a PFS of 15.2 months in EGFR mutation-positive patients versus 4.4 months in EGFR wild type disease patients and a median OS of 18.9 months. The most common AEs were rash (77.1%), paronychia (20.8%), hyperbilirubinemia (16.7%), and diarrhea (14.6%).42
